[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''Sir John Wilfred Stanier''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|MBE}} (6 October 1925 – 10 November 2007) was a senior [[British Army]] officer who was [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]] from 1982 to 1985. He was the first person after the [[Second World War]] to become the professional head of the British Army without having seen active service in that war or any subsequent campaign.

==Army career==
[[File:Marlborough College Court.jpg|thumb|left|Marlborough College where Stanier was educated]]
Stanier was born in [[Sawbridgeworth]] in [[Essex]], the son of Harold Allan Stanier and Penelope Rose Stanier (née Price).<ref name=tele>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1569158/Field-Marshal-Sir-John-Stanier.html |title=Obituary: Field Marshal Sir John Stanier|date=13 November 2007|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> His father was badly wounded in the [[World War I|First World War]], but was employed by Spedan Lewis to manage his farms.<ref name=inde>{{cite web|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article3157766.ece |title=Obituary: Field Marshal Sir John Stanier |publisher=The Independent|date=14 November 2007|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> He was educated at [[Marlborough College]]<ref name=pg269>Heathcote, Anthony pg 269</ref> and took a short wartime course at [[Merton College, Oxford]].<ref name=tele/><ref name="MCreg">{{cite book|editor1-last=Levens|editor1-first=R.G.C.|title=Merton College Register 1900-1964|date=1964|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|page=343}}</ref> He volunteered for the Army in 1943, and having trained at [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] and [[Bovington]],<ref name=tele/> was commissioned into the [[7th Queen's Own Hussars]] on 19 April 1946.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=37580|supp=yes|startpage=2548|date=24 May 1946|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> Promoted to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 16 October 1948,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=38430|supp=yes|startpage=5437|date=12 October 1948|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> he served with the intelligence branch in [[Italy]] in 1949 before being posted to the [[British Army of the Rhine]] in 1950.<ref name=tele/> He was promoted to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 6 October 1952<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=39662|supp=yes|startpage=5263|date=3 October 1952|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and became an instructor at the [[Mons Officer Cadet School]] in [[Aldershot]] in April 1954, before attending the [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1957.<ref name=pg269/> Following the merger of his regiment with the [[3rd The King's Own Hussars]], he became an officer in the [[Queen's Own Hussars]] in 1958<ref name=pg269/> and was posted to the Directorate of Military Operations at the [[War Office]], before being appointed military assistant to [[William Stratton (British Army officer)|Sir William Stratton]], Vice-Chief of the [[Imperial General Staff]] in July 1959.<ref name=tele/> Promoted to [[major]] on 6 October 1959,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=41834|supp=yes|startpage=6267|date=2 October 1959|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> he was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] in the [[New Year Honours]] 1961.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=42231|supp=yes|startpage=8895|date=27 December 1960|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> He attended the [[Joint Service Defence College|Joint Services Staff College]] and, from 1962, commanded the tanks in "C" Squadron of his regiment in Germany,<ref name=tele/> before returning to Camberley as Director of Studies in 1963.<ref name=tele/>
[[File:Staff College, Camberley.jpg|thumb|left|Stanier served as Commandant of the Staff College, Camberley]]
Stainer was not selected to command the Queen's Own Hussars.<ref name=tele/> Disappointed, he considered leaving the Army,<ref name=tele/> but was pleasantly surprised, having transferred to the [[Royal Scots Greys]] on 1 January 1966,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=43852|supp=yes|startpage=12221|date=28 December 1965|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> to be promoted to [[lieutenant colonel]] on 2 May 1966<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=44069|supp=yes|startpage=8605|date=29 July 1966|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and made [[Commanding Officer]] of the Royal Scots Greys.<ref name=pg269/> He joined the staff of the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]] in December 1968,<ref name=pg269/> and was then promoted two ranks to [[brigadier]] on 31 December 1969<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=45013|supp=yes|startpage=215|date=5 January 1970|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and took command of [[20th Armoured Brigade (United Kingdom)|20th Armoured Brigade]] in the [[British Army of the Rhine]] in January 1970.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/20bde/bde_comd.htm 20th Armoured Brigade list of commanders]</ref>  After serving as the Army's director of public relations in London from 1971, he was appointed [[General Officer Commanding]] [[1st Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|1st Armoured Division]] on 3 November 1973<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=46120|supp=yes|startpage=13177|date=5 November 1973|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> with the substantive rank of [[major general]] from 21 January 1974.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=46188|supp=yes|startpage=847|date=21 January 1974|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> He became Commandant at the [[Staff College, Camberley]] on 22 December 1975.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=46769|supp=yes|startpage=16296|date=23 December 1975|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>

He was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]] 1978,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=47549|supp=yes|startpage=6230|date=2 June 1978|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and became [[List of senior officers of the British Army#Vice Chiefs of the Imperial General Staff|Vice Chief of the Imperial General Staff]]<ref name="page270">Heathcote, Anthony pg 270</ref> with the rank of [[lieutenant general]] on 1 June 1978.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=47566|supp=yes|startpage=7133|date=12 June 1978|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> The [[Challenger 1|Challenger tank]] was brought into service during his period in this post.<ref name=tele/> Promoted to full [[general]] on 1 January 1981, he was made [[Commander-in-Chief, Land Forces|Commander-in-Chief, UK Land Forces]] in April 1981.<ref name="page270"/>  He became [[ADC General]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] from 7 April 1981,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=48589|supp=yes|startpage=5767|date=16 April 1981|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> was advanced to [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]] 1982<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=49008|supp=yes|startpage=2|date=11 June 1982|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and became [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]] on 1 August 1982.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=49069|supp=yes|startpage=10134|date=2 August 1982|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> He was the first person after the [[Second World War]] to become the professional head of the [[British Army]] without having seen active service in that war or any subsequent campaign.<ref name=tele/> He was promoted to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 10 July 1985<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=50226|supp=yes|startpage=11147|date=12 August 1985|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> on retirement from the British Army.<ref name="page270"/>

He was also Colonel of the [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]] from 18 January 1979<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=47752|supp=yes|startpage=987|date=22 January 1979|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> to 6 May 1984,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=49735|supp=yes|startpage=6805|date=14 May 1984|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> and Colonel Commandant of the [[Royal Armoured Corps]] from 1 April 1982<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=48964|supp=yes|startpage=5649|date=26 April 1982|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref> to 1 August 1985.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=50233|supp=yes|startpage=11483|date=19 August 1985|accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>

In retirement he served as chairman of the [[Royal United Service Institution]] from 1986 to 1989.<ref name=tele/> He was [[Constable of the Tower|Constable of the Tower of London]] from 1990 to 1996.<ref name=tele/>  His book ''War and the Media'', co-authored with Miles Hudson, was published in 1997.<ref name=tele/> He was a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of [[Hampshire]] from 1987, and lived near [[Hartley Wintney]].<ref name=tele/>

His interests included [[fly fishing]], [[sailing]] and [[Equestrianism|horse riding]] and he was also President of the Hampshire branch of the [[British Red Cross|British Red Cross Society]] from 1986 to 1994.<ref name=tele/> He was also a Member of the Council of [[Marlborough College]].<ref name=tele/> He died on 10 November 2007.<ref name=tele/>

==Family==
In 1955 he married Cicely Constance Lambert; they had four daughters.<ref name=tele/>

